%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Overview}
%******************************************************************************

%claude:
Before showing the source code of [[acid]] and [[ratrace]] in
the following chapters, I first give an overview of the general
principles of tracers and debuggers, then describe the services
that [[ratrace]] and [[acid]] provide.

\section{Tracer principles}

%yoann: first technique to debug, printf! A classic
%claude:
The most basic debugging technique is [[printf]]: insert
print statements into the code and observe the output.
This works, but it requires modifying the program,
recompiling, and knowing where to look in advance.

%less: add ref with codes are work that mention a lot the only use of printf
% for debugging.
%logging is good, see partial trace of execution. Traces are good.

%yoann: ratrace does automatic logging without any printf, based on syscalls
% a good boundary, a good granularity. There is also now 'ltrace'.
%claude:
A {system call tracer} provides automatic logging without
any modification to the program. It intercepts every
system call the program makes---[[open]], [[read]],
[[write]], [[fork]], etc.---and prints the call name,
arguments, and return value. System calls are a good
boundary for tracing because they represent every
interaction between the program and the operating system.
%
This makes tracers an effective first tool for many bugs:
a program that fails silently might be trying to open a
file that does not exist, or writing to a full disk.
The tracer reveals these issues immediately, especially
when the program does not check its error codes.
Linux's [[strace]] and \plan's [[ratrace]] work this way.
There is also [[ltrace]] on Linux, which traces library
calls rather than system calls.

% Good first way to debug issues, to get more insight on what's going on.
% Simple, and very effective at finding many bugs, like
% no more space in /tmp. Especially when people don't check
% return error code, at least see the call to create a file in /tmp

\section{[[ratrace]] services}

<<function usage (tracers/ratrace.c)>>=
void
usage(void)
{
    fprint(STDERR, "Usage: ratrace [-c cmd [arg...]] | [pid]\n");
    exits("usage");
}
@

%claude:
%The command-line interface of [[ratrace]] is simple:
%\begin{verbatim}
%$ ratrace [-c cmd [arg...]] | [pid]
%\end{verbatim}

[[ratrace]] has two modes of operation:
\begin{itemize}

\item [[ratrace -c ls /dev]] starts [[ls /dev]] and traces
its system calls from the beginning.

\item [[ratrace 1234]] attaches to an already running process
with pid 1234 and traces its subsequent system calls.

\end{itemize}

%claude:
Here is an example tracing a simple [[echo hello]] command:
\begin{verbatim}
$ ratrace -c echo hello
...
66 echo Pwrite 796c 1 0xa488/"hello." 6 -1hello
 = 6 "" 2000135 2000135
...
66 echo Exits 30bf 0/""
\end{verbatim}

Each line shows the system call name, its arguments (file
descriptor, buffer address, size, offset), and the return
value after the [[ = ]]. Here we can see [[echo]] calling
[[Pwrite]] to write 6 bytes ([[hello\n]]) to file
descriptor~1 (standard output), followed by [[Exits("")]]
to terminate successfully.
%
When a program fails mysteriously, [[ratrace]] often reveals
the cause immediately. For instance, an [[Open]] returning
$-1$ or a [[Pread]] on a file descriptor that was never
opened points directly to the bug.

%yoann: explain on example above = 6 on line after because actually hello output after -1 so mixed program output and ratrace output
%claude:
Note that in the output above, the [[= 6]] return value
appears on the line \emph{after} the [[Pwrite]] call.
This is because the program's own output ([[hello]])
is interleaved with [[ratrace]]'s trace output---both
write to standard error, so they mix on screen. The
[[-1]] in the [[Pwrite]] line is the file offset argument,
not the return value.

\section{Debugger principles}

% Program to control another program.
% Naive = interpreter, cf Machine.nw. Full control, but very very slow.
% => need hardware (and kernel) debugging support! so fast!

% simple: external child process that you can control (thx to kernel
% features) modify the code in memory at the breakpoint address given
% by the user to generate a fault => when execute and reach breakpoint
% we will be given back the hand. => efficient!
% less: Can use same trick for watchpoint? when access some memory area?
% hmm but then has to invalidate the whole page? so some false positives.

% Debugging process, debugged process.

% For some advanced inspection features the debugger needs metadata,
% generated by the assembler, the compiler, and the linker. Symbol tables.
% See "Debugging Support" chapters in Assembler.nw, Compiler.nw,
% Linker.nw We will recall the essential things below.

% But without any medata the debugger can already do a lot if again
% the kernel provide good introspection feature on the debugged
% children process. The registers values, the memory state.

% Another good support from the kernel is the Broken state
% in Kernel.nw. It's convenient because when segfault,
% got the core dump, but actually under plan9 the process is put
% in a Broken state and can be debugged by
%  db <pid>
% Awesome (remember efuns.byte crashes).

%claude:
A {debugger} is a program that controls another program.
One naive approach is full interpretation (as in the
\book{Emulator}), which gives total control but is far
too slow for real programs. Instead, debuggers rely on
hardware and kernel support to control a target process
efficiently.

%claude:
The basic mechanism is simple: the debugger is a separate
process that can read and write the target's memory and
registers through kernel facilities ([[/proc]] on \plan,
[[ptrace]] on Linux). To set a {breakpoint}, the debugger
replaces an instruction at the desired address with one
that causes a fault (e.g., [[BKPT]] on ARM, [[INT 3]] on
x86). When the target reaches that address, the fault
stops execution and gives control back to the debugger.
The debugger can then inspect registers and memory, and
resume execution after restoring the original instruction.

\subsection{Breakpoint}

%claude:
A {breakpoint} stops execution at a specific address.
As described above, the debugger patches the instruction
at the target address to cause a fault, waits for the
fault, then restores the original instruction. Breakpoints
can be conditional (stop only when a condition is true)
or counted (stop only after the $n$-th hit).

\subsection{Watchpoint}

%claude:
A {watchpoint} (or data breakpoint) stops execution when
a specific memory location is read or written. This is
useful for finding out what code modifies a variable.
%
Hardware watchpoints use the processor's debug registers
to monitor an address without slowing down execution.
Software watchpoints can be implemented by marking the
memory page as inaccessible and catching the resulting
page fault, though this is slower.

\subsection{Inspector}

%claude:
The debugger can {inspect} the state of the stopped process.
%registers, memory, the call stack. 
%
Even without any metadata, a debugger can do a lot if the
kernel provides good introspection on the target process:
register values, memory contents, the call stack.
%and the ability to single-step.

However, for a good user experience, the debugger
needs {metadata} generated by the toolchain: a {symbol table}
mapping addresses to function and variable names (from
the linker), and {line number information} mapping addresses
to source lines (from the compiler). The ``Debugging Support''
chapters in the \book{Assembler}, \book{Compiler}, and
\book{Linker} describe how this metadata is generated.

%claude:
With symbol table information, the debugger can display function
names and variable values instead of raw addresses and numbers.
%
With type information (e.g., from [[acid]]'s type descriptions
or DWARF on other systems), it can even display structured data
types like structs and arrays in a readable format.

\subsection{Disassembler}

%claude:
A {disassembler} converts machine code back into assembly
mnemonics, allowing the user to see what instructions the
processor will execute. This is the reverse of what the
assembler does. The debugger typically uses a library
(e.g., [[libmach]] in \plan) to decode the binary
instructions at a given address.

\subsection{Source-level debugging}

%claude:
With line number information from the compiler, the debugger
can display source code instead of assembly, set breakpoints
on source lines, and step one source statement at a time.
This requires the debugger to map between addresses and
source positions in both directions. Source-level debugging
is what most developers expect, but it requires cooperation
from the entire toolchain: the compiler must emit line tables,
the linker must preserve them, and the debugger must read them.


\section{[[acid]] services}

<<function usage (acid/main.c)>>=
void
usage(void)
{
    fprint(STDERR, "usage: acid [-kqw] [-l library] [-m machine] [pid] [file]\n");
    exits("usage");
}
@


%claude:
%The command-line interface of [[acid]] is:
%\begin{verbatim}
%$ acid [-kqw] [-l library] [-m machine] [pid] [textfile]
%\end{verbatim}
%

The main flags are:
\begin{itemize}

\item [[-l library]]: load an [[acid]] library file at startup.
Libraries provide higher-level debugging functions; for instance,
[[acid -l truss]] loads a system call tracer written entirely
in [[acid]]'s own language (see Section~\ref{sec:truss}).

\item [[-k]]: debug kernel state rather than user state
(see Section~\ref{sec:acid-k})

\item [[-w]]: allow modifying the text file (for patching binaries).
(see Section~\ref{sec:acid-w})

\item [[-m machine]]: specify the CPU type for disassembly.
(see Section~\ref{sec:acid-m})

\end{itemize}

You can specify a running process by [[pid]], or a binary
by [[textfile]] (defaulting to [[8.out]]). At startup,
[[acid]] loads standard function definitions from
[[/lib/acid/port]] and architecture-specific functions
from [[/lib/acid/$objtype]].
%old: was from /sys/lib/acid/...

%claude:
The key functions available at the [[acid: ]] prompt include:
[[new()]] (start the program),
[[bpset()]] (set a breakpoint),
[[cont()]] (continue execution),
[[step()]] (single-step),
[[next()]] (statement-step),
[[stk()]] (print call stack with arguments),
[[src()]] (show source around an address),
[[asm()]] (disassemble),
[[regs()]] (print registers),
and [[print()]] (display a value).
% classic gdb-like, just more verbose
%
Because these are regular [[acid]] functions defined in
the standard library---not built-in commands---the user can
redefine them or write new ones to automate complex
debugging tasks.
% power of language! programmable debugger

\section{Debugging [[hello_bug.c]]}
%alt: [[hello.core]] ? [[hello.bug]] A simple debugging session

%claude:
Here is a typical [[acid]] debugging session on a small program
that divides by zero:

%coupling: ROOT/tests/acid/hello_bug.c
<<hello_bug.c>>=
#include <u.h>
#include <libc.h>

int foo(int x, int y) { 
    return x / y;
}

int bar(int a, int b) {
    return foo(a, b) + 3;
}

void
main(int argc, char **argv)
{
    int x, y, z;
    x = 41 + argc;
    y = argc - 1;
    z = bar(x, y);
    print("%d %d %d\n", x, y, z);
    exits(nil);
}
@


