acid: asm(foo)
foo 0x00001020  MOVL x+0x0(FP),AX
foo+0x4 0x00001024   CDQ
foo+0x5 0x00001025   IDIVL AX,y+0x4(FP)
foo+0x9 0x00001029   RET
bar 0x0000102a  SUBL  $0x8,SP
acid: regs()
PC  0x00001025 foo+0x5 /tests/acid/hello_bug.c:5
SP  0xcfffef20 ECODE 0xe010068d EFLAG 0x00000286
CS  0x00000023 DS 0x0000001b SS 0x0000001b
GS  0x0000001b FS 0x0000001b ES 0x0000001b
TRAP    0x000000000 divide error
AX  0x0000002a BX 0x0000002a CX 0x00000000 DX  0x00000000
DI  0x0002e641 SI 0x00000000 BP 0xcfffba48
acid:
\end{verbatim}

[[cont()]] resumes execution, but this time the program hits a
divide-by-zero fault inside [[foo]] before reaching any breakpoint.
The kernel stops the process and [[acid]] reports the fault:
``divide error'' at [[foo+0x5]], the [[IDIVL]] instruction.
%
[[src(*PC)]] confirms we are on line~5, the [[return x / y]]
statement. Now we can inspect the arguments that caused the
fault: [[*foo:y]] reads the value of parameter [[y]] from
[[foo]]'s stack frame and shows [[0x00000000]]---the zero
divisor. [[*foo:x]] shows [[0x0000002a]] (42).
The \verb+\d+ format suffix in \verb+*foo:x\d+ displays
it as decimal.
%
[[asm(foo)]] disassembles [[foo]], showing the three-instruction
body: load [[x]] into [[AX]], sign-extend with [[CDQ]], then
[[IDIVL]] which divides [[AX]] by [[y]]---the faulting instruction.
%
Finally, [[regs()]] dumps the full register state at the time of
the fault: [[AX=0x2a]] (42, the dividend), [[CX=0x0]] (the
divisor), and [[TRAP=divide error]].
This is the typical acid debugging workflow: inspect source,
read variables, check assembly, examine registers.

