\subsection{Setting [[registers]] and [[bpinst]]}

%claude:
[<varreg()>] creates an [[acid]] variable for each machine
register (e.g., [[R0]], [[R1]], [[PC]], [[SP]]) using the
register list from [[mach->reglist]]. Each variable's value
is set to the register's offset in the [[/proc/<pid>/regs]]
file, so that [[*R0]] reads the actual register value from
the live process via [[cormap]]. It also creates the
[[bpinst]] variable containing the breakpoint instruction
bytes, and a [[registers]] list variable for enumeration.

<<function [[varreg]]>>=
/// main -> attachfiles -> readtext -> <>
void
varreg(void)
{
    Lsym *l;
    Value *v;
    Reglist *r;
    List **tail, *li;

    l = mkvar("registers");
    v = l->v;
    v->set = 1;
    v->type = TLIST;

    v->l = 0;
    tail = &v->l;

    for(r = mach->reglist; r->rname; r++) {
        l = mkvar(r->rname);
        v = l->v;
        v->set = 1;
        v->ival = r->roffs;
        v->fmt = r->rformat;
        v->type = TINT;

        li = al(TSTRING);
        li->string = strnode(r->rname);
        li->fmt = 's';

        *tail = li;
        tail = &li->next;
    }

    if(machdata == nil)
        return;

    l = mkvar("bpinst");	/* Breakpoint text */
    v = l->v;
    v->type = TSTRING;
    v->fmt = 's';
    v->set = 1;
    v->string = gmalloc(sizeof(String));
    v->string->len = machdata->bpsize;
    v->string->string = gmalloc(machdata->bpsize);
    memmove(v->string->string, machdata->bpinst, machdata->bpsize);
}
@



\section{[[loadmodule()]]} % and [[loadmoduleobjtype()]]}

%claude:
At startup, [[acid]] loads two standard library files:
[[/lib/acid/port]] (architecture-independent functions like
[[new()]], [[bpset()]], [[cont()]], [[stk()]], [[src()]]) and
[[/lib/acid/<arch>]] (architecture-specific functions). Additional
libraries can be loaded with [[-l]]. Loading a module simply
means parsing it with [<yyparse()>]---since the parser
executes [[defn]] statements as it goes, the function
definitions become available immediately.

<<[[main()]](acid) load modules>>=
