%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Parsing}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:parsing}

% Lexing and parsing in same chapter this time; we also explain less this time
% as similar to parsing in Compiler, Assembler, Make, Shell, Utilities (awk, ...)
% Main focus of this book is understand debugging, not parsing.

% main -> yyparse -> yylex

%claude:
This chapter presents the lexer and parser for the [[acid]]
language. The lexer and parser follow the same patterns seen
in the \book{Compiler}, \book{Shell}, and \book{Assembler}:
a hand-written lexer feeding a yacc-generated parser. I will
not explain them in as much detail, since the focus of this
book is on debugging, not parsing.

\section{Files management}
% similar to what was done by cpp with #include, but here acid include
% and no macro, just include

%claude:
Like the C preprocessor's [[#include]], [[acid]] can read
input from multiple files (the standard library, user libraries,
and stdin). The [[IOstack]] structure maintains a stack of
open input sources. When [[acid]] encounters an [[include()]]
call or loads a module, it pushes a new [[IOstack]] entry;
when that file is exhausted, it pops back to the previous source.

\subsection{[[IOstack]]}

<<struct [[IOstack]]>>=
struct IOstack
{
    // ref_own<string>    included filename or "<stdin>"  or "<string>"
    char	*name;
    // option<ref_own<Biobuf>> (None when <string>)
    Biobuf	*fin;

    // saved global line to be restored in popio()
    int	line;

    <<[[IOstack]] other fields>>
    // Extra
    <<[[IOstack]] extra fields>>
};
@

<<global [[lexio]]>>=
// list<ref_own<IOstack> next = lexio.prev
IOstack *lexio;
@
<<[[IOstack]] extra fields>>=
IOstack	*prev;
@

\subsection{[[pushfile()]]}

% file can be nil when called from main first time to read stdin

<<function [[pushfile]]>>=
/// main | loadmodule -> <>
void
pushfile(char *file)
{
    Biobuf *b;
    IOstack *io;

    if(file)
        b = Bopen(file, OREAD);
    else{
        b = Bopen("/fd/0", OREAD);
        file = "<stdin>";
    }

    <<[[pushfile()]] sanity check [[b]]>>

    io = malloc(sizeof(IOstack));
    <<[[pushfile()]] sanity check [[io]]>>
    io->name = strdup(file);
    <<[[pushfile()]] sanity check [[io->name]]>>

    io->line = line;
    line = 1;
    io->fin = b;
    io->text = nil;

    // add_list(io, lexio)
    io->prev = lexio;
    lexio = io;
}
@
%$

<<[[pushfile()]] sanity check [[b]]>>=
if(b == nil)
    error("pushfile: %s: %r", file);
@
<<[[pushfile()]] sanity check [[io]]>>=
if(io == nil)
    fatal("no memory");
@
<<[[pushfile()]] sanity check [[io->name]]>>=
if(io->name == nil)
    fatal("no memory");
@



\subsection{[[restartio()]], [[popio()]]}

<<function [[restartio]]>>=
/// main -> yyparse; <>
void
restartio(void)
{
    Bflush(lexio->fin);
    Binit(lexio->fin, STDIN, OREAD);
}
@
% why need that?


% return false when done, so can be used as while(popio())

<<function [[popio]]>>=
/// loadmodule | error -> <>
bool
popio(void)
{
    IOstack *s;

    if(lexio == nil)
        return false;

    if(lexio->prev == nil){
        if(lexio->fin)
            restartio();
        return false;
    }
    // else

    if(lexio->fin)
        Bterm(lexio->fin);
    else
       <<[[popio()]] when no [[fin]]>>
    free(lexio->name);

    // restore global line
    line = lexio->line;

    // s = pop_list(lexio)
    s = lexio;
    lexio = s->prev;
    free(s);

    return true;
}
@



\section{Lexer}

\subsection{[[lexc()]] and [[unlexc()]]}

%claude:
[<lexc()>] is the low-level character reader. It reads from
[[lexio->fin]] (a [[Biobuf]] file) or from [[lexio->text]]
(an in-memory string, used by [[interpret()]]). [<unlexc()>]
pushes one character back.

<<function [[lexc]]>>=
int
lexc(void)
{
    int c;

    if(lexio->fin) {
        c = Bgetc(lexio->fin);
        <<[[lexc()]] if [[gotint]]>>
        return c;
    }
    // else
    <<[[lexc()]] when no [[fin]]>>
}
@
% why -1? why not Eof?

<<function [[unlexc]]>>=
void
unlexc(int s)
{
    if(s == '\n')
        line--;

    if(lexio->fin)
        Bungetc(lexio->fin);
    else
        <<[[unlexc()]] when no [[fin]]>>
}
@


\subsection{[[yylex()]]}

%claude:
[<yylex()>] is the main lexer function, called by the
yacc-generated parser. It skips whitespace, handles comments
([[//]] style), and dispatches on the first character of
each token. An important detail: in interactive mode, a
bare newline (not inside braces) is returned as [[;]],
making semicolons optional at the prompt.

<<function [[yylex]]>>=
/// main -> yyparse -> <>
int
yylex(void)
{
    int c;
    <<[[yylex]] other locals>>

loop:
    Bflush(bout);
    c = lexc();
    switch(c) {
    <<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>
    }
}
@

<<acid constants>>=
Eof		= -1,
@
% Code returned by Bgetc? so reuse same for yylex

<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case Eof:
    <<[[yylex()]] when [[Eof]], if [[gotint]]>>
    return Eof;
@


<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '.':
    c = lexc();
    unlexc(c);
    if(isdigit(c))
        return numsym('.');

    return '.';

@

<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
default:
    return numsym(c);
@

<<global [[symbol]]>>=
char	symbol[Strsize];
@

<<function [[numsym]]>>=
int
numsym(char first)
{
    char *p;
    int c;
    <<[[numsym()]] locals>>

    symbol[0] = first;
    p = symbol;

    <<[[numsym()]] if number>>
    // else
    <<[[numsym()]] when symbol>>
}
@
%$


\subsection{Spaces and comments}

<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case ' ':
case '\t':
    goto loop;
@


<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '/':
    c = lexc();
    if(c == '/') {
        eatnl();
        goto loop;
    }
    unlexc(c);
    return '/';

@

<<function [[eatnl]]>>=
void
eatnl(void)
{
    int c;

    line++;
    for(;;) {
        c = lexc();
        if(c == Eof)
            error("eof in comment");
        if(c == '\n')
            return;
    }
}
@

\subsection{Newlines}

<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '\n':
    line++;
    if(!interactive)
        goto loop;
    if(stacked) {
        print("\t");
        goto loop;
    }
    // else when interactive and not stacked
    return ';';
@


\subsection{Numbers}

<<[[numsym()]] locals>>=
bool isbin, isfloat, ishex;
char *sel;
@

<<[[numsym()]] if number>>=
ishex = false;
isbin = false;
isfloat = false;
if(first == '.')
    isfloat = true;

if(isdigit(*p++) || isfloat) {
    for(;;) {
        c = lexc();
        if(c < 0)
            error("%d: <eof> eating symbols", line);

        if(c == '\n')
            line++;
        sel = "01234567890.xb";
        if(ishex)
            sel = "01234567890abcdefABCDEF";
        else if(isbin)
            sel = "01";
        else if(isfloat)
            sel = "01234567890eE-+";

        if(strchr(sel, c) == 0) {
            unlexc(c);
            break;
        }
        if(c == '.')
            isfloat = true;
        if(!isbin && c == 'x')
            ishex = true;
        if(!ishex && c == 'b')
            isbin = true;
        *p++ = c;
    }
    *p = '\0';
    if(isfloat) {
        yylval.fval = atof(symbol);
        return Tfconst;
    }

    if(isbin)
        yylval.ival = strtoull(symbol+2, 0, 2);
    else
        yylval.ival = strtoull(symbol, 0, 0);
    return Tconst;
}
@


\subsection{Characters}

<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '\'':
    c = lexc();
    if(c == '\\')
        yylval.ival = escchar(lexc());
    else
        yylval.ival = c;
    c = lexc();
    if(c != '\'') {
        error("missing '");
        unlexc(c);
    }
    return Tconst;

@

<<function [[escchar]]>>=
int
escchar(char c)
{
    int n;
    char buf[Strsize];

    if(c >= '0' && c <= '9') {
        n = 1;
        buf[0] = c;
        for(;;) {
            c = lexc();
            if(c == Eof)
                error("%d: <eof> in escape sequence", line);
            if(strchr("0123456789xX", c) == 0) {
                unlexc(c);
                break;
            }
            if(n >= Strsize)
                error("string escape too long");
            buf[n++] = c;
        }
        buf[n] = '\0';
        return strtol(buf, 0, 0);
    }

    n = cmap[c];
    if(n == 0)
        return c;
    return n-1;
}
@

<<global [[cmap]]>>=
char cmap[256] =
{
    ['0']	'\0'+1,
    ['n']	'\n'+1,
    ['r']	'\r'+1,
    ['t']	'\t'+1,
    ['b']	'\b'+1,
    ['f']	'\f'+1,
    ['a']	'\a'+1,
    ['v']	'\v'+1,
    ['\\']	'\\'+1,
    ['"']	'"'+1,
};
@


\subsection{Strings}

<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '"':
    eatstring();
    return Tstring;
@

<<function [[eatstring]]>>=
void
eatstring(void)
{
    int esc, c, cnt;
    char buf[Strsize];

    esc = 0;
    for(cnt = 0;;) {
        c = lexc();
        switch(c) {
        case Eof:
            error("%d: <eof> in string constant", line);

        case '\n':
            error("newline in string constant");
            goto done;

        case '\\':
            if(esc)
                goto Default;
            esc = 1;
            break;

        case '"':
            if(esc == 0)
                goto done;

            /* Fall through */
        default:
        Default:
            if(esc) {
                c = escchar(c);
                esc = 0;
            }
            buf[cnt++] = c;
            break;
        }
        if(cnt >= Strsize)
            error("string token too long");
    }
done:
    buf[cnt] = '\0';
    yylval.string = strnode(buf);
}
@

<<acid constants>>=
Strsize		= 4096,
@


\subsection{Operators and punctuations}

<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '(':
case ')':
case '[':
case ']':
case ';':
case ':':
case ',':
case '~':
case '?':
case '*':
case '@':
case '^':
case '%':
    return c;
@

<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '{':
    stacked++;
    return c;
case '}':
    stacked--;
    return c;

@

<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '!':
    c = lexc();
    if(c == '=')
        return Tneq;
    unlexc(c);
    return '!';

@

<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '+':
    c = lexc();
    if(c == '+')
        return Tinc;
    unlexc(c);
    return '+';

@

<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '&':
    c = lexc();
    if(c == '&')
        return Tandand;
    unlexc(c);
    return '&';

@
<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '=':
    c = lexc();
    if(c == '=')
        return Teq;
    unlexc(c);
    return '=';

@
<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '|':
    c = lexc();
    if(c == '|')
        return Toror;
    unlexc(c);
    return '|';

@
<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '<':
    c = lexc();
    if(c == '=')
        return Tleq;
    if(c == '<')
        return Tlsh;
    unlexc(c);
    return '<';

case '>':
    c = lexc();
    if(c == '=')
        return Tgeq;
    if(c == '>')
        return Trsh;
    unlexc(c);
    return '>';

@
<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '-':
    c = lexc();

    if(c == '>')
        return Tindir;

    if(c == '-')
        return Tdec;
    unlexc(c);
    return '-';

@

\subsection{Format [[X\F]]}

<<[[yylex]] other locals>>=
extern char vfmt[];
@

<<[[yylex()]] switch [[c]] cases>>=
case '\\':
    c = lexc();
    if(strchr(vfmt, c) == 0) {
        unlexc(c);
        return '\\';
    }
    yylval.ival = c;
    return Tfmt;

@

\subsection{Symbols}

<<[[numsym()]] locals>>=
Lsym *s;
@
<<[[numsym()]] when symbol>>=
for(;;) {
    c = lexc();
    if(c < 0)
        error("%d <eof> eating symbols", line);
    if(c == '\n')
        line++;
    if(c != '_' && c != '$' && c <= '~' && !isalnum(c)) {	/* checking against ~ lets UTF names through */
        unlexc(c);
        break;
    }
    *p++ = c;
}

*p = '\0';

s = look(symbol);
if(s == 0)
    s = enter(symbol, Tid);

yylval.sym = s;
return s->lexval;
@

\subsection{Keywords}

%claude:
Keywords are handled through the symbol table rather than
special-casing them in the lexer. [<kinit()>] enters all
keywords into the hash table with their token codes; when
[<numsym()>] looks up an identifier, keywords are found
and their [[lexval]] (e.g., [[Tif]], [[Twhile]], [[Tfn]])
is returned instead of [[Tid]].

<<global [[keywds]]>>=
struct keywd
{
    char	*name;
    int	terminal;
}
keywds[] =
{
    "do",	Tdo,
    "if",	Tif,
    "then",	Tthen,
    "else",	Telse,
    "while",	Twhile,
    "loop",	Tloop,

    "head",	Thead,
    "tail",	Ttail,
    "append",	Tappend,

    "defn",	Tfn,
    "return",	Tret,
    "local",	Tlocal,
    "aggr",	Tcomplex,
    "union",	Tcomplex,
    "adt",	Tcomplex,
    "complex",	Tcomplex,
    "delete",	Tdelete,
    "whatis",	Twhat,
    "eval",	Teval,
    "builtin",	Tbuiltin,

    0,		0
};
@

<<function [[kinit]]>>=
void
kinit(void)
{
    int i;
    
    for(i = 0; keywds[i].name; i++) 
        enter(keywds[i].name, keywds[i].terminal);
}
@

% use enter() too



\section{Grammar}

\subsection{Overview}

%claude:
The [[acid]] grammar is specified in yacc format and is
relatively small---about 150 lines of rules. The grammar
is C-like with a few differences: [[defn]] instead of
function declarations, [[then]]/[[do]] keywords after conditions,
list operations ([[head]], [[tail]], [[append]]), and
[[complex]]/[[aggr]] for type descriptions. Most grammar
rules build AST nodes using [<an()>].

<<acid/dbg.y>>=
%{
#include <u.h>
#include <libc.h>
#include <bio.h>
#include <mach.h>

#include "acid.h"
%}
<<union yacc>>
<<type declarations>>
<<priority and associativity declarations>>
<<token declarations>>
%%
<<grammar>>
%%
@

<<[[union yacc]] other fields>>=
Node	*node;
@
<<type declarations>>=
%type <node> expr monexpr term stmnt name args zexpr slist
%type <node> member members mname castexpr idlist
%type <sym> zname
@
% most rules return a node

<<priority and associativity declarations>>=
%left	';'
%right	'='
%left	Tfmt
%left	Toror
%left	Tandand
%left	'|'
%left	'^'
%left	'&'
%left	Teq Tneq
%left	'<' '>' Tleq Tgeq
%left	Tlsh Trsh
%left	'+' '-'
%left	'*' '/' '%'
%right	Tdec Tinc Tindir '.' '[' '('
@

<<grammar>>=
prog
  : /* empty */
  | prog bigstmnt
  ;

<<statements rules>>
<<members rules>>
<<expressions rules>>
<<name rules>>
<<other rules>>
@


<<name rules>>=
name 
  : Tid
  {
   $$ = an(ONAME, ZN, ZN);
   $$->sym = $1;
  }
  | Tid ':' name
  {
   $$ = an(OFRAME, $3, ZN);
   $$->sym = $1;
  }
  ;
@

<<name rules>>=
zname
  : 
  /* empty */
  { $$ = 0; }
  | Tid
  ;
@


\subsection{Definitions}

%claude:
The [[bigstmnt]] rule is the top-level entry point. It handles
three cases: a statement (which is immediately executed via
[<execute()>] and then garbage-collected), a function definition
([[defn name(args) \{ body \}]]), and a complex type declaration
([[aggr name \{ members \}]]). The immediate execution is the
key design choice---[[acid]] does not separate parsing from
execution for interactive statements.

<<statements rules>>=
bigstmnt
  : stmnt
  {
   /* make stmnt a root so it isn't collected! */
   mkvar("_thiscmd")->proc = $1;
   execute($1);
   mkvar("_thiscmd")->proc = nil;
   gc();
   if(interactive)
      Bprint(bout, "acid: ");
  }
  | Tfn Tid '(' args ')' zsemi '{' slist '}'
  {
   $2->proc = an(OLIST, $4, $8);
  }
  | Tfn Tid
  {
   $2->proc = nil;
  }
  | Tcomplex name '{' members '}' ';'
  {
   defcomplex($2, $4);
  }
  ;
@

% execute! 

<<other rules>>=
zsemi
  : /* empty */
  | ';' zsemi
@


\subsection{Statements}

<<statements rules>>=
stmnt
  : zexpr ';'
  | '{' slist '}'
  {
   $$ = $2;
  }
  | Tif expr Tthen stmnt
  {
   $$ = an(OIF, $2, $4);
  }
  | Tif expr Tthen stmnt Telse stmnt
  {
   $$ = an(OIF, $2, an(OELSE, $4, $6));
  }
  | Tloop expr ',' expr Tdo stmnt
  {
   $$ = an(ODO, an(OLIST, $2, $4), $6);
  }
  | Twhile expr Tdo stmnt
  {
   $$ = an(OWHILE, $2, $4);
  }
  | Tret expr ';'
  {
   $$ = an(ORET, $2, ZN);
  }
  | Tlocal idlist
  {
   $$ = an(OLOCAL, $2, ZN);
  }
  | Tcomplex Tid name ';'
  {
   $$ = an(OCOMPLEX, $3, ZN);
   $$->sym = $2;
  }
  ;

@


<<other rules>>=
idlist
  : Tid
  {
   $$ = an(ONAME, ZN, ZN);
   $$->sym = $1;
  }
  | idlist ',' Tid
  {
   $$ = an(ONAME, $1, ZN);
   $$->sym = $3;
  }
  ;

@


<<statements rules>>=
slist
  : stmnt
  | slist stmnt
  {
   $$ = an(OLIST, $1, $2);
  }
  ;
@

\subsection{Expressions}

<<expressions rules>>=
expr
  : castexpr
  | expr '*' expr { $$ = an(OMUL, $1, $3); }
  | expr '/' expr { $$ = an(ODIV, $1, $3); }
  | expr '%' expr { $$ = an(OMOD, $1, $3); }
  | expr '+' expr { $$ = an(OADD, $1, $3); }
  | expr '-' expr { $$ = an(OSUB, $1, $3); }

  | expr Trsh expr { $$ = an(ORSH, $1, $3); }
  | expr Tlsh expr { $$ = an(OLSH, $1, $3); }

  | expr '<' expr  { $$ = an(OLT, $1, $3); }
  | expr '>' expr  { $$ = an(OGT, $1, $3); }
  | expr Tleq expr { $$ = an(OLEQ, $1, $3); }
  | expr Tgeq expr { $$ = an(OGEQ, $1, $3); }
  | expr Teq expr  { $$ = an(OEQ, $1, $3); }
  | expr Tneq expr { $$ = an(ONEQ, $1, $3); }

  | expr '&' expr { $$ = an(OLAND, $1, $3); }
  | expr '^' expr	{ $$ = an(OXOR, $1, $3); }
  | expr '|' expr { $$ = an(OLOR, $1, $3); }

  | expr Tandand expr { $$ = an(OCAND, $1, $3); }
  | expr Toror expr   { $$ = an(OCOR, $1, $3); }

  | expr '=' expr { $$ = an(OASGN, $1, $3); }
  | expr Tfmt { $$ = an(OFMT, $1, con($2)); }
  ;
@
<<expressions rules>>=
castexpr
  : monexpr
  | '(' Tid ')' monexpr
  {
   $$ = an(OCAST, $4, ZN);
   $$->sym = $2;
  }
  ;
@
<<expressions rules>>=
monexpr
  : term
  | '*' monexpr {	$$ = an(OINDM, $2, ZN);	}
  | '@' monexpr {	$$ = an(OINDC, $2, ZN);	}
  | '+' monexpr {	$$ = an(OADD, $2, ZN); }
  | '-' monexpr {	$$ = con(0); $$ = an(OSUB, $$, $2); }

  | Tdec monexpr { $$ = an(OEDEC, $2, ZN); }
  | Tinc monexpr { $$ = an(OEINC, $2, ZN); }

  | Thead monexpr	{ $$ = an(OHEAD, $2, ZN); }
  | Ttail monexpr	{ $$ = an(OTAIL, $2, ZN); }
  | Tappend monexpr ',' monexpr { $$ = an(OAPPEND, $2, $4); }
  | Tdelete monexpr ',' monexpr {	$$ = an(ODELETE, $2, $4); }

  | '!' monexpr {	$$ = an(ONOT, $2, ZN); }
  | '~' monexpr {	$$ = an(OXOR, $2, con(-1)); }
  | Teval monexpr { $$ = an(OEVAL, $2, ZN);}
  ;
@
<<expressions rules>>=
term
  : '(' expr ')'
  {
   $$ = $2;
  }
  | '{' args '}'
  {
   $$ = an(OCTRUCT, $2, ZN);
  }
  | term '[' expr ']'
  {
   $$ = an(OINDEX, $1, $3);
  }
  | term Tdec
  {
   $$ = an(OPDEC, $1, ZN);
  }
  | term '.' Tid
  {
   $$ = an(ODOT, $1, ZN);
   $$->sym = $3;
  }
  | term Tindir Tid
  {
   $$ = an(ODOT, an(OINDM, $1, ZN), ZN);
   $$->sym = $3;
  }
  | term Tinc
  {
   $$ = an(OPINC, $1, ZN);
  }
  | name '(' args ')'
  {
   $$ = an(OCALL, $1, $3);
  }
  | Tbuiltin name '(' args ')'
  {
   $$ = an(OCALL, $2, $4);
   $$->builtin = 1;
  }
  | name
  | Tconst
  {
   $$ = con($1);
  }
  | Tfconst
  {
   $$ = an(OCONST, ZN, ZN);
   $$->type = TFLOAT;
   $$->fmt = 'f';
   $$->fval = $1;
  }
  | Tstring
  {
   $$ = an(OCONST, ZN, ZN);
   $$->type = TSTRING;
   $$->string = $1;
   $$->fmt = 's';
  }
  | Twhat zname
  {
   $$ = an(OWHAT, ZN, ZN);
   $$->sym = $2;
  }
  ;
@


<<expressions rules>>=
args
  : zexpr
  | args ','  zexpr
  {
   $$ = an(OLIST, $1, $3);
  }
  ;
@

<<expressions rules>>=
zexpr
  : /* empty */
  { $$ = 0; }
  | expr
  ;
@


\subsection{Complex}

<<members rules>>=
members
  : member
  | members member
  {
   $$ = an(OLIST, $1, $2);
  }
  ;

mname
  : Tid
  {
   $$ = an(ONAME, ZN, ZN);
   $$->sym = $1;
  }
  ;

member
  : Tconst Tconst mname ';'
  {
   $3->ival = $2;
   $3->fmt = $1;
   $$ = $3;
  }
  | Tconst mname Tconst mname ';'
  {
   $4->ival = $3;
   $4->fmt = $1;
   $4->right = $2;
   $$ = $4;
  }
  | mname Tconst mname ';'
  {
   $3->ival = $2;
   $3->left = $1;
   $$ = $3;
  }
  | '{' members '}' ';'
  {
   $$ = an(OCTRUCT, $2, ZN);
  }
  ;
@


%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Interpreting}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:interpreting}

%claude:
This chapter presents the [[acid]] interpreter: the tree-walking
evaluator that executes AST nodes produced by the parser.
The interpreter is split into two parts: [<execute()>] handles
statements (control flow, assignments, function calls), while
the [[expr()]] macro dispatches expression evaluation through
a function pointer table [[expop]].

\section{[[execute()]]}

%claude:
[<execute()>] is the main statement executor. It pattern-matches
on the node's opcode: [[OLIST]] sequences two statements,
[[OIF]] and [[OWHILE]] implement control flow, [[OLOCAL]]
declares local variables, and [[ORET]] returns from a function
via [[longjmp]]. For expression statements, it falls through
to [[expr()]] and prints the result using [[prnt]].

<<function [[execute]]>>=
/// main (acidmap) | ?? -> <>
void
execute(Node *n)
{
    Node *l, *r;
    Value *v;
    Node res;
    <<[[execute()]] other locals>>

    gc();
    <<[[execute()]] if [[gotint]]>>
    if(n == nil)
        return;
    <<[[execute()]] if big statements count>>

    l = n->left;
    r = n->right;
    switch(n->op) {
    <<[[execute()]] switch [[n->op]] cases>>
    }
}
@


<<[[execute()]] other locals>>=
static int stmnt;
@
<<[[execute()]] if big statements count>>=
if(stmnt++ > 5000) {
    Bflush(bout);
    stmnt = 0;
}
@
% ?? seems dead


