%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Source level C Debugging}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:source-level}
% C support

%claude:
Source-level debugging requires cooperation between the
compiler (which generates line number tables), the linker
(which preserves them in the executable), and [[libmach]]
(which provides lookup functions like [[fileline()]] and
[[pc2line()]]). The [[acid]] library functions [[src()]]
and [[Bsrc()]] use these to display source code around
a given address.

\section{[[acid: src()]]}

%alt: when using db
%\chapter{Command Input}
%\chapter{Command Parsing}
%\chapter{Commands}
%\chapter{[[acid]]}


%******************************************************************************
\chapter{The [[acid]] Library}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:acid-library}

%claude:
Most of [[acid]]'s user-facing functionality is implemented not
in C but in [[acid]]'s own language, in library files loaded at
startup. This is the essence of [[acid]]'s design: the C code
provides low-level primitives (process control, memory access,
expression evaluation), and the [[acid]] library builds
higher-level debugging commands on top. Users can redefine any
library function or write new ones.

\section{[[/lib/acid/port]]}

%claude:
The portable library defines the core debugging functions:
[[new()]] (start a process, set a breakpoint at [[main]],
continue to it), [[bpset()]]/[[bpdel()]] (breakpoint management),
[[cont()]] (continue execution), [[step()]] (single-step),
[[stk()]] (print call stack), [[src()]] (show source),
[[asm()]] (disassemble), [[regs()]] (print registers),
[[mem()]] (display memory), and [[stkrace()]] (stack trace).
These functions use the builtins from the Interpreting and
Process Control chapters.

\subsection{[[acid: new()]]}

%claude:
The [[new()]] function is the typical entry point for a
debugging session. It clears the breakpoint list, calls
[[newproc()]] to fork/exec the target, sets a breakpoint
at [[main]], continues to it, then removes the breakpoint.
After [[new()]], the target is stopped at the first
instruction of [[main]], ready for inspection.

\section{[[/lib/acid/arm]]}
%\section{[[386]]}

%\section{...} lots of files

%claude:
The architecture-specific library files define functions
that depend on register names and calling conventions:
[[regs()]] prints the architecture's register set,
[[stk()]] uses the frame pointer chain to walk the stack,
and [[step()]] uses [[follow()]] to find the next
instruction(s) and single-step correctly over branches
and delay slots.

\section{[[/lib/acid/truss]]}
\label{sec:truss}
% ratrace using acid program

%claude:
The [[truss]] library implements system call tracing
entirely in [[acid]]'s own language---it is a software-only
alternative to [[ratrace]]. Loading it with [[acid -l truss]]
adds functions that set breakpoints on system call entry
points, decode the arguments, and print them in a readable
format. This demonstrates [[acid]]'s programmability: even
a tracer can be written as a debugging script.


%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Advanced Features}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:advanced-features}

%claude:
This chapter covers features that go beyond basic debugging:
memory leak detection and code coverage (both implemented as
[[acid]] library scripts), binary patching with [[-w]],
kernel debugging with [[-k]], remote debugging with [[-r]],
and cross-architecture debugging with [[-m]].

\section{Memory leak detection}

%/lib/acid/leak

% also leak.rc, umem.rc, kmem.rc

%claude:
The [[/lib/acid/leak]] library implements memory leak detection
by tracking [[malloc]] and [[free]] calls. It sets breakpoints on
the memory allocator functions and records each allocation in
an [[acid]] list. When the user calls [[leaks()]], it reports
allocations that were never freed. This is similar in spirit to
Valgrind's leak detector but implemented entirely as an [[acid]]
script, running the target at native speed between breakpoints.

\section{Code coverage}

%/lib/acid/coverage

%claude:
The [[/lib/acid/coverage]] library implements basic code coverage
by setting breakpoints on every function entry point and recording
which ones are hit during execution. After a test run, it reports
which functions were never called.

\section{Modifying code: [[acid -w]]}
\label{sec:acid-w}

%claude:
Normally [[acid]] opens the executable file read-only.
With [[-w]], it opens it for writing too, allowing the user
to patch the binary on disk---for instance, to replace
an instruction with a [[NOP]] or change a constant.
This is a powerful but dangerous feature; changes are
permanent in the file.

<<global wtflag (acid/globals.c)>>=
bool	wtflag;
@

<<[[main()]](acid) command line processing>>=
case 'w':
    wtflag = true;
    break;
@


<<[[attachfiles()]] if [[wtflag]]>>=
if(wtflag)
    text = open(aout, ORDWR);
@

\section{Kernel debugging: [[acid -k]]}
\label{sec:acid-k}

% have a special chapter for Kernel debugging, with ktrace too?

%http://ddeville.me/2015/08/kernel-debugging-with-lldb-and-vmware-fusion/

%claude:
With [[-k]], [[acid]] debugs the kernel rather than a user
process. It reads kernel registers from [[/proc/<pid>/kregs]]
instead of [[/proc/<pid>/regs]], and uses the kernel's
text file as the executable. This requires a running kernel
process to attach to (specified by PID).

<<global [[kernel]]>>=
int	kernel;
@
%todo: bool

<<[[main()]](acid) command line processing>>=
case 'k':
    kernel++;
    break;
@

<<[[main()]](acid) if kernel and no pid>>=
if(kernel) {
    fprint(STDERR, "acid: -k requires a pid\n");
    usage();
}
@

