\section{Remote debugging: [[acid -r]]}

%claude:
Remote debugging exploits \plan's [[import]] command: you
can import a remote machine's [[/proc]] into your local
namespace, then run [[acid -r]] against it as if the process
were local. The [[-r]] flag implies [[-k]] (kernel mode)
and defaults PID to~1. This is a beautiful demonstration of
\plan's ``everything is a file'' philosophy---the same
[[/proc]] interface works across network boundaries.

<<global [[remote]]>>=
int	remote;
@
%todo: bool

<<[[main()]](acid) if argc and remote adjust [[aout]]>>=
if(remote)
    aout = argv[0];
@

<<[[main()]](acid) if not argc and remote adjust [[aout]]>>=
if(remote)
    aout = "/mips/9ch";
@


<<[[main()]](acid) command line processing>>=
case 'r':
    pid = 1;
    remote++;
    kernel++;
    break;
@


\section{Cross architecture debugging: [[acid -m]]}
\label{sec:acid-m}

% was also db -m

% import /proc !! beautiful. Power of 9p and libmach.

%claude:
With [[-m]], [[acid]] can debug a binary compiled for a
different architecture than the host. For instance, you
can run [[acid -m arm]] on an x86 machine to disassemble
and debug an ARM binary. Combined with [[import]]'ed
[[/proc]] from a remote ARM machine, this gives full
cross-architecture debugging. The [[-m]] flag overrides
the automatic architecture detection from [<crackhdr()>].

<<global [[mtype]]>>=
static char*	mtype;
@

<<[[main()]](acid) command line processing>>=
case 'm':
    mtype = ARGF();
    break;
@

<<[[main()]](acid) sanity check [[mtype]]>>=
if(mtype && machbyname(mtype) == 0)
    print("unknown machine %s", mtype);
@



<<[[readtext()]] if [[mtype != nil]]>>=
if(mtype != nil){
    symmap = newmap(0, 1);
    if(symmap == 0)
        print("%s: (error) loadmap: cannot make symbol map\n", argv0);
    length = 1<<24;
    d = dirfstat(text);
    if(d != nil){
        length = d->length;
        free(d);
    }
    setmap(symmap, text, 0, length, 0, "binary");
    return;
}
@



%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Advanced Topics}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:advanced-topics}

\section{Time travel}
% checkpoints

%claude:
Time-travel debugging---the ability to step backward through
execution---is not implemented in [[acid]], but the concept
is worth mentioning. Tools like [[rr]] on Linux achieve this
by recording every non-deterministic event (system call results,
signal deliveries, thread scheduling) during execution, then
replaying deterministically. [[ocamldebug]] achieves a simpler
form by periodically checkpointing the bytecode interpreter
state. In principle, [[acid]]'s [[/proc]] interface could support
a checkpoint-based approach: save process memory at each
breakpoint and restore it to ``go back.''

%alt: \section{Cross machine debugging}
%alt: \section{Kernel debugging}

%\section{Signals and notes}


%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Conclusion}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:conclusion}

% snoopy, tracer/debugger for networking issues!

%claude:
You now know how the \plan debugger [[acid]] works,
to the smallest details, and more generally how many
debuggers work.

%claude:
A debugger may seem like magic---setting breakpoints,
inspecting registers, single-stepping through
instructions---but the underlying mechanism is
remarkably simple: replace an instruction with one
that faults, let the kernel stop the process, then
read and write the process's memory and registers
through [[/proc]]. The entire debugger fits in a
few thousand lines of C because the kernel's
[[/proc]] file system does the heavy lifting:
[[ctl]] for control, [[mem]] for memory access,
[[regs]] for registers, [[text]] for the executable.
%
Along the way, you have seen a command-line
interpreter with its own expression parser and
address arithmetic, the [[libmach]] library for
reading symbol tables and disassembling instructions,
and the breakpoint state machine that saves and
restores the original instruction around each stop.

\section{Patterns and techniques}

%claude:
These techniques apply far beyond debugging:
\begin{itemize}

\item \emph{Synthetic file system}: exposing process state
as files under [[/proc]] rather than a special API. Linux's
[[/proc]] and [[/sys]], Docker's cgroup filesystem, and
FUSE all use the same idea: expose internal state as files
and you get scriptability for free.

\item \emph{Save/restore state machine}: save the original
instruction, write a trap, wait for the fault, restore,
single-step, re-insert. This save/modify/restore cycle
is the same pattern as database transactions and text
editor undo/redo.

\item \emph{REPL with expression language}: an interactive
command loop with its own address syntax and expression
grammar. This is the natural interface whenever a user
needs to explore a stateful system---SQL consoles, Redis
CLI, and browser developer tools all follow it.

\item \emph{Abstraction layer for binary formats}:
[[libmach]] hides the details of the object format behind
a uniform interface for reading symbols, disassembling
instructions, and navigating executables. LLVM's
[[libObject]] (ELF, Mach-O, COFF behind one API), image
libraries (one API for PNG, JPEG, GIF), and
JDBC (one API for many databases) follow the same
strategy. It lets
higher-level code work with the \emph{meaning} of the
data without caring about its \emph{encoding}.

\end{itemize}

\section{Connections to other books}

%claude:
\begin{itemize}

\item \book{Kernel}: the kernel provides the
infrastructure that makes debugging possible---the
[[/proc]] file system, the [[Broken]] process state
(which lets you attach to a crashed process without
needing a core dump), and the [[note]] mechanism for
delivering signals to the debugged process.

\item \book{Linker}: [[5l]] generates the symbol
table and line number information that [[acid]] reads
through [[libmach]] to map addresses to function
names and source lines.

\item \book{Assembler}: understanding the ARM
instruction set is essential for reading disassembly
output and understanding how breakpoints work
(replacing an instruction with [[BKPT]]).

\item \book{Compiler}: source-level debugging
requires metadata generated by [[5c]]---local
variable locations, type information, and the
mapping between source lines and machine addresses.

%\item \book{Libcore}: covers [[libmach]], the
%library that [[db]] uses to parse executables,
%read symbol tables, and disassemble machine code.

\end{itemize}

\section{Beyond the \plan debugger}

%claude:
Modern debuggers have evolved far beyond [[acid]] and [[db]]'s
command-line interface. Here are some of the
features they provide:
\begin{itemize}

\item \emph{DWARF debug information}: [[acid]] reads
\plan's simple symbol table and line number format.
Modern debuggers (GDB, LLDB) consume DWARF, a rich
and complex standard that encodes variable locations
(including optimized-out variables and register
assignments), type hierarchies, inlined function
boundaries, and macro definitions. DWARF is what
makes source-level debugging of optimized code
possible.

\item \emph{Scriptable debuggers}: GDB has a
Python scripting interface, and LLDB is built
around a Python API from the ground up. \plan's
[[acid]] takes a different approach---it is a
debugger built as an interpreter for a custom
C-like language, letting users write debugging
scripts that understand data structures and can
walk linked lists or dump hash tables.

\item \emph{Time-travel debugging}: tools like
[[rr]] (for Linux) can record an entire program
execution and replay it deterministically, allowing
you to step backwards as well as forwards. This is
transformative for debugging race conditions and
heisenbugs.

\item \emph{Graphical and IDE integration}:
most developers today use debuggers through their
IDE (VS Code, CLion, Xcode), with visual breakpoint
management, variable watches, and call stack
navigation. The Debug Adapter Protocol (DAP)
provides a standard interface between editors and
debuggers.

\item \emph{Dynamic tracing}: Linux's [[strace]]
is functionally similar to \plan's [[ratrace]], but
tools like DTrace and eBPF go much further,
allowing programmable tracing of kernel and
user-space functions with minimal overhead. These
have largely replaced traditional system call
tracing for production debugging.

\item \emph{Memory debuggers}: tools like Valgrind
and AddressSanitizer detect memory errors (use after
free, buffer overflows, uninitialized reads) by
instrumenting memory accesses---a category of
debugging that [[acid]] does not address at all.
%TODO? actually /lib/acid/leak ? also malloc.acid useful?

\end{itemize}

%claude:
The core idea, however, has not changed: a debugger
is a program that controls another program, using
kernel facilities to stop, inspect, and modify the
target's execution. [[acid]] presents this idea in its
simplest form, with the \plan [[/proc]] interface
making the mechanism especially transparent.

